<entry>
<author><name><![CDATA[blargg]]></name></author>
<updated>2009-01-29T07:32:16-07:00</updated>
<published>2009-01-29T07:32:16-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=4795&amp;p=42469#p42469</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=4795&amp;p=42469#p42469"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Can NES music be NSF-rip protected?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=4795&amp;p=42469#p42469"><![CDATA[
- Make the code very timing-dependent, so any changes will disrupt critical APU writes.<br />- Use VRAM for variables and music data.<br />- Access the PPU in ways that are hard to follow or remove.<br />- Require an obscure mapper.<br />- Rely on unofficial instructions.<br />- Make code rely on absolute addresses. For example, have the high byte of an address also be executed as an opcode.<br />- Put some hard-to-find writes to the NSF bank switch registers.<br /><br />I'm sure others can come up with more off-the-wall ideas.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=17">blargg</a> — Thu Jan 29, 2009 7:32 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
